data.content:
Here's what's happening:

## The Problem

In C# 14, new built-in span conversions cause **`MemoryExtensions.Contains`** (which takes `ReadOnlySpan<T>`) to be selected instead of **`Enumerable.Contains`** (which takes `IEnumerable<T>`) when you call `.Contains()` on an array.

`MemoryExtensions.Contains` cannot be represented in an expression tree, so the expression tree interpreter throws at runtime.

## The Fix

Force the compiler to bind to `Enumerable.Contains` by casting or calling explicitly:

```csharp
// Option 1: Cast to IEnumerable<int>
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);

// Option 2: Use .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 3: Explicit static call
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

Any of these disambiguates overload resolution so the expression tree gets the `Enumerable` method it can actually represent.
